1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:05,320
Hello everyone and welcome to EnglishPod.
大家好，欢迎收听EnglishPod。

2
00:00:05,320 --> 00:00:06,320
My name is Marco.
我是Marco。

3
00:00:06,320 --> 00:00:11,380
My name is Catherine and today we're talking a little bit about going to sleep or not being
我是Catherine，今天我们聊一聊关于入睡或者睡不着的话题。

4
00:00:11,380 --> 00:00:12,380
able to sleep.
无法入睡。

5
00:00:12,380 --> 00:00:13,380
That's right.
没错。

6
00:00:13,380 --> 00:00:18,960
We are having some sleeping problems and we're actually going to check out a couple of words
我们遇到了一些睡眠问题，现在我们要在“词汇预览”环节看看几个相关的词。

7
00:00:18,960 --> 00:00:24,440
related to this topic right now on Vocabulary Preview.
词汇预览。

8
00:00:24,440 --> 00:00:25,440
Vocabulary Preview.
词汇预览。

9
00:00:25,440 --> 00:00:32,680
Okay, so the first word is actually the technical word that describes being unable to sleep.
好的，第一个词其实是描述无法入睡的专业术语。

10
00:00:32,680 --> 00:00:33,920
It's called insomnia.
它叫失眠症。

11
00:00:33,920 --> 00:00:34,920
Right.
对。

12
00:00:34,920 --> 00:00:39,120
So if you have insomnia, it means that you can't fall asleep.
所以如果你有失眠症，意思是你无法入睡。

13
00:00:39,120 --> 00:00:40,120
You can't sleep.
你睡不着。

14
00:00:40,120 --> 00:00:41,120
Okay.
好的。

15
00:00:41,120 --> 00:00:42,700
So this is a pretty serious condition.
所以这是一种相当严重的情况。

16
00:00:42,700 --> 00:00:46,960
For example, if you have insomnia and you don't sleep for three or four nights, you're
比如，如果你有失眠症，连续三四个晚上不睡觉，

17
00:00:46,960 --> 00:00:49,000
not going to do very well at work, right?
你在工作上肯定表现不好，对吧？

18
00:00:49,000 --> 00:00:50,000
Right.
对。

19
00:00:50,000 --> 00:00:52,840
Or if you're studying, you're tired at school, you can't concentrate.
或者如果你在学习，在学校里会很累，无法集中注意力。

20
00:00:52,840 --> 00:00:55,040
So it's a very big problem.
所以这是个很大的问题。

21
00:00:55,040 --> 00:00:56,040
What's that other word though?
那另一个词是什么呢？

22
00:00:56,040 --> 00:00:59,400
We have insomnia, but we also have another interesting disorder.
我们有失眠症，但还有另一种有趣的障碍。

23
00:00:59,400 --> 00:01:00,400
Right.
对。

24
00:01:00,400 --> 00:01:06,880
If somebody is able to sleep but walks while they're sleeping, that person is called a
如果有人能睡着，但睡觉时会走路，那个人就被称为

25
00:01:06,880 --> 00:01:07,880
sleepwalker.
梦游者。

26
00:01:07,880 --> 00:01:08,880
That's right.
没错。

27
00:01:08,880 --> 00:01:11,840
And you don't actually just have to walk to be a sleepwalker.
而且梦游者不一定只是走路。

28
00:01:11,840 --> 00:01:17,280
You can do any number of strange things like basically acting like you're awake when you're
你可以做各种奇怪的事情，基本上就像醒着一样行动，但其实

29
00:01:17,280 --> 00:01:18,280
not.
你并没有醒。

30
00:01:18,280 --> 00:01:19,280
Exactly.
正是。

31
00:01:19,280 --> 00:01:23,760
So some people get up and walk, actually go outside.
所以有些人会起床走路，甚至走到外面。

32
00:01:23,760 --> 00:01:24,880
Some people get dressed.
有些人会穿衣服。

33
00:01:24,880 --> 00:01:26,480
Some people go downstairs and cook.
有些人会下楼做饭。

34
00:01:26,480 --> 00:01:27,480
Yeah, that's right.
是的，没错。

35
00:01:27,480 --> 00:01:31,200
And the worst is the people who eat because they gain weight and they don't know why.
最糟糕的是那些吃东西的人，因为他们会发胖，却不知道原因。

36
00:01:31,200 --> 00:01:32,200
Exactly.
正是。

37
00:01:32,200 --> 00:01:35,520
So sleepwalking is what you do.
所以梦游就是你所做的事情。

38
00:01:35,520 --> 00:01:37,520
And if you do this, you're called a sleepwalker.
如果你这样做，你就被称为梦游者。

39
00:01:37,520 --> 00:01:38,520
Okay.
好的。

40
00:01:38,520 --> 00:01:40,720
Sleepwalk is the verb.
“梦游”是动词。

41
00:01:40,720 --> 00:01:42,440
Sleepwalker is the noun or the person.
“梦游者”是名词，指人。

42
00:01:42,440 --> 00:01:43,440
All right.
好的。

43
00:01:43,440 --> 00:01:48,160
So we've taken a look at two words that we're going to find in our dialogue today.
我们已经看了两个今天对话中会出现的词。

44
00:01:48,160 --> 00:01:55,160
Why don't we go now and listen to the dialogue for the first time.
我们现在为什么不先去听一遍对话呢？

45
00:01:55,160 --> 00:02:00,320
Alex, what's up with you?
Alex，你怎么了？

46
00:02:00,320 --> 00:02:01,320
You look dreadful.
你看起来糟透了。

47
00:02:01,320 --> 00:02:02,320
Hey, Jill.
嘿，Jill。

48
00:02:02,320 --> 00:02:03,320
I don't know.
我不知道。

49
00:02:03,320 --> 00:02:07,040
I've been having trouble sleeping these past few weeks.
过去几周我一直睡不好。

50
00:02:07,040 --> 00:02:10,520
I usually lie in bed for hours trying to get to sleep.
我通常躺在床上几个小时想入睡。

51
00:02:10,520 --> 00:02:14,560
I've tried stretching and different breathing techniques before going to bed.
我试过睡前拉伸和不同的呼吸技巧。

52
00:02:14,560 --> 00:02:17,680
I've tried eating and not eating different foods.
我试过吃或不吃不同的食物。

53
00:02:17,680 --> 00:02:20,080
I've even tried counting sheep.
我甚至试过数羊。

54
00:02:20,080 --> 00:02:24,440
And then when I finally get to sleep, I have these really disturbing nightmares.
然后当我终于睡着时，又会做非常令人不安的噩梦。

55
00:02:24,440 --> 00:02:28,520
So I usually wake up in a panic and more tired than before I went to sleep.
所以我通常会在恐慌中醒来，比睡前更累。

56
00:02:28,520 --> 00:02:29,520
Wow.
哇。

57
00:02:29,520 --> 00:02:31,480
Maybe you should get that checked out.
也许你应该去检查一下。

58
00:02:31,480 --> 00:02:33,200
Maybe you're stressed.
也许你压力太大了。

59
00:02:33,200 --> 00:02:34,640
Just take some sedatives.
吃点镇静剂吧。

60
00:02:34,640 --> 00:02:36,160
Works for me.
对我挺管用的。

61
00:02:36,160 --> 00:02:40,540
Every so often having some melatonin on hand helps me when I have trouble sleeping.
偶尔手边备点褪黑素，在我睡不好时会有帮助。

62
00:02:40,540 --> 00:02:43,040
It works on all kinds of sleeping disorders.
它对各种睡眠障碍都有效。

63
00:02:43,040 --> 00:02:46,280
It's the stuff pilots use to regulate their sleeping patterns.
这是飞行员用来调节睡眠模式的东西。

64
00:02:46,280 --> 00:02:47,440
I heard of that.
我听说过那个。

65
00:02:47,440 --> 00:02:49,800
But does that apply to Alex's situation?
但那适用于Alex的情况吗？

66
00:02:49,800 --> 00:02:51,320
Yeah, sure.
是的，当然。

67
00:02:51,320 --> 00:02:52,320
Why not?
为什么不呢？

68
00:02:52,320 --> 00:02:57,360
Sounds like he only has transient insomnia since it's a recent thing so taking melatonin
听起来他只是有短暂性失眠，因为这是最近才出现的，所以吃褪黑素

69
00:02:57,360 --> 00:02:58,640
should do the trick.
应该能解决问题。

70
00:02:58,640 --> 00:03:01,680
But shouldn't he be looking into why it's been happening?
但他不应该查查为什么会这样吗？

71
00:03:01,680 --> 00:03:04,880
Well, aren't you the little psychologist?
哦，你还真像个心理医生啊？

72
00:03:04,880 --> 00:03:06,520
Our buddy's having trouble sleeping.
我们的哥们儿睡不好觉。

73
00:03:06,520 --> 00:03:08,000
It's easy and curable.
这很容易解决，也能治好。

74
00:03:08,000 --> 00:03:11,120
It's not something freakish like if he was a sleepwalker.
又不是像他梦游那样怪异的事情。

75
00:03:11,120 --> 00:03:18,360
Well, there's that too.
嗯，那倒也是。

76
00:03:18,360 --> 00:03:19,360
Alright we're back.
好了，我们回来了。

77
00:03:19,360 --> 00:03:27,000
So obviously this person not only has insomnia but also has nightmares, sleepwalks, a mess.
所以很明显这个人不仅失眠，还有噩梦、梦游，一团糟。

78
00:03:27,000 --> 00:03:28,000
That's right.
没错。

79
00:03:28,000 --> 00:03:31,120
And you can tell when someone hasn't been sleeping well.
你能看出一个人没睡好。

80
00:03:31,120 --> 00:03:37,280
They have that look like there's bags under their eyes or they just look really tired.
他们看起来就像眼睛下有眼袋，或者就是很疲惫的样子。

81
00:03:37,280 --> 00:03:41,720
And so the friend here says, Alex, you look dreadful.
所以这里的朋友说，亚历克斯，你看起来糟透了。

82
00:03:41,720 --> 00:03:43,120
That's right, dreadful.
没错，糟透了。

83
00:03:43,120 --> 00:03:47,600
So this is an adjective and it's a way to describe someone that looks terrible.
这是一个形容词，用来形容某人看起来状态很差。

84
00:03:47,600 --> 00:03:48,960
You look horrible.
你看起来糟糕极了。

85
00:03:48,960 --> 00:03:49,960
You look tired.
你看起来很累。

86
00:03:49,960 --> 00:03:50,960
You look sleepy.
你看起来很困。

87
00:03:50,960 --> 00:03:51,960
That's right.
没错。

88
00:03:51,960 --> 00:03:53,320
So this is not a compliment.
所以这不是一句赞美。

89
00:03:53,320 --> 00:03:56,260
This is something that you say when you're worried about someone.
这是当你担心某人时说的话。

90
00:03:56,260 --> 00:04:00,840
So for example, if someone's really, really tired, you say, you look dreadful.
比如，如果有人非常非常累，你会说，你看起来糟透了。

91
00:04:00,840 --> 00:04:06,040
Or if someone is wearing very dirty clothes, they don't look like they went home yesterday,
或者如果有人穿着很脏的衣服，看起来像昨晚没回家，

92
00:04:06,040 --> 00:04:07,400
you say, what's wrong?
你会说，怎么了？

93
00:04:07,400 --> 00:04:08,400
You look dreadful.
你看起来糟透了。

94
00:04:08,400 --> 00:04:09,400
Right.
对。

95
00:04:09,400 --> 00:04:13,400
I think you can also use it to describe objects or maybe food, right?
我觉得你也可以用它来形容物品或食物，对吧？

96
00:04:13,400 --> 00:04:14,880
This lasagna is dreadful.
这份千层面糟透了。

97
00:04:14,880 --> 00:04:16,280
It means it's very bad.
意思是它非常难吃。

98
00:04:16,280 --> 00:04:19,880
And you don't want to say that to the person who cooked it, of course.
当然，你不会对做饭的人这么说。

99
00:04:19,880 --> 00:04:20,880
Exactly.
正是。

100
00:04:20,880 --> 00:04:26,520
Alright, so the person obviously because is suffering from insomnia looks dreadful.
好了，所以这个人显然因为失眠而看起来糟透了。

101
00:04:26,520 --> 00:04:30,400
And he was explaining what he does to try to fall asleep.
他解释了自己尝试入睡的方法。

102
00:04:30,400 --> 00:04:36,400
For example, counting sheep, stretching, and he also said that he tried different breathing
比如数羊、拉伸，他还说试过不同的呼吸

103
00:04:36,400 --> 00:04:37,400
techniques.
技巧。

104
00:04:37,400 --> 00:04:43,320
Okay, so basically a technique is an approach to something, a kind of method.
好的，所以技巧基本上是一种做某事的方法或方式。

105
00:04:43,320 --> 00:04:45,960
But in this case, we're talking about breathing techniques.
但在这里，我们说的是呼吸技巧。

106
00:04:45,960 --> 00:04:51,780
So for some people, one breathing technique is breathing in through your nose and breathing
对有些人来说，一种呼吸技巧是通过鼻子吸气，然后

107
00:04:51,780 --> 00:04:54,120
out through your mouth.
通过嘴巴呼气。

108
00:04:54,120 --> 00:04:55,120
Like that.
像这样。

109
00:04:55,120 --> 00:04:56,280
That's one kind of technique.
这是一种技巧。

110
00:04:56,280 --> 00:04:59,600
So a technique, as you say, is a way of doing something.
所以技巧，如你所说，是一种做事的方式。

111
00:04:59,600 --> 00:05:03,600
So breathing techniques are different ways of breathing.
所以呼吸技巧就是不同的呼吸方式。

112
00:05:03,600 --> 00:05:07,560
So maybe you will relax, so maybe you'll fall asleep, things like this.
这样你可能会放松，然后可能入睡，诸如此类。

113
00:05:07,560 --> 00:05:08,560
Exactly.
正是。

114
00:05:08,560 --> 00:05:10,840
It's one of those things that you might learn about in a yoga class, for example.
这是你在瑜伽课上可能会学到的东西之一，比如。

115
00:05:10,840 --> 00:05:12,640
There's different breathing techniques.
有各种不同的呼吸技巧。

116
00:05:12,640 --> 00:05:13,640
Right.
对。

117
00:05:13,640 --> 00:05:18,040
And you can combine techniques with other words as well, adding the ing.
你也可以把技巧和其他词组合起来，加上ing。

118
00:05:18,040 --> 00:05:24,520
For example, you have walking techniques, maybe to put less stress on your knees.
比如，有走路技巧，可能为了减轻膝盖压力。

119
00:05:24,520 --> 00:05:26,720
Or running techniques, swimming techniques.
或者跑步技巧、游泳技巧。

120
00:05:26,720 --> 00:05:29,680
I think there's a technique for almost everything.
我觉得几乎每件事都有技巧。

121
00:05:29,680 --> 00:05:32,520
Just about anything you can do, there's a technique for it.
几乎任何你能做的事，都有对应的技巧。

122
00:05:32,520 --> 00:05:33,520
Right.
对。

123
00:05:33,520 --> 00:05:34,520
Yeah, yeah, for sure.
是啊，是啊，确实。

124
00:05:34,520 --> 00:05:35,520
All right.
好的。

125
00:05:35,520 --> 00:05:40,720
And well, moving on, he was talking about his nightmares and he described his nightmares
然后，继续往下，他谈到了自己的噩梦，并形容他的噩梦

126
00:05:40,720 --> 00:05:42,280
as disturbing.
令人不安。

127
00:05:42,280 --> 00:05:43,720
He has disturbing nightmares.
他有令人不安的噩梦。

128
00:05:43,720 --> 00:05:48,520
Okay, well, I think this is an important word to cover here, Marco, because we've heard
好的，我觉得这是一个需要讲解的重要词汇，马可，因为我们之前听过

129
00:05:48,520 --> 00:05:51,560
the verb to disturb before.
动词“打扰”。

130
00:05:51,560 --> 00:05:52,960
Like I'm sorry to disturb you.
比如“抱歉打扰你”。

131
00:05:52,960 --> 00:05:54,840
It means I'm sorry to bother you.
意思是“抱歉打扰你”。

132
00:05:54,840 --> 00:05:56,680
But disturbing is an adjective.
但“令人不安”是形容词。

133
00:05:56,680 --> 00:05:59,680
It describes something that makes me very uncomfortable.
它描述的是让我非常不舒服的东西。

134
00:05:59,680 --> 00:06:00,680
Right?
对吧？

135
00:06:00,680 --> 00:06:01,680
Right.
对。

136
00:06:01,680 --> 00:06:06,880
So, for example, a lot of times in the news, we see very disturbing images, car accidents
所以，比如，新闻里经常看到非常令人不安的画面，车祸

137
00:06:06,880 --> 00:06:09,640
or fires or bombs.
或火灾或炸弹。

138
00:06:09,640 --> 00:06:12,880
And what's disturbing is when you see human beings who have been hurt.
令人不安的是当你看到人类受伤的情景。

139
00:06:12,880 --> 00:06:18,160
So images that make you really uncomfortable or sad, these are disturbing.
所以那些让你非常不舒服或难过的画面，就是令人不安的。

140
00:06:18,160 --> 00:06:19,160
Exactly.
正是。

141
00:06:19,160 --> 00:06:24,240
So disturbing nightmares are nightmares that are not very pleasant.
所以令人不安的噩梦就是不太愉快的噩梦。

142
00:06:24,240 --> 00:06:26,320
They make him scared, maybe, or uncomfortable.
它们可能让他害怕，或者不舒服。

143
00:06:26,320 --> 00:06:27,320
Right.
对。

144
00:06:27,320 --> 00:06:29,240
Like a dream, for example, where your parents die.
比如一个梦，你父母去世了。

145
00:06:29,240 --> 00:06:31,000
It's pretty disturbing.
这相当令人不安。

146
00:06:31,000 --> 00:06:32,000
Exactly.
正是。

147
00:06:32,000 --> 00:06:33,000
All right.
好的。

148
00:06:33,000 --> 00:06:35,160
And well, one of his friends recommended, you know what?
然后，他的一位朋友建议，你知道吗？

149
00:06:35,160 --> 00:06:36,360
Stop with all of this.
别搞这些了。

150
00:06:36,360 --> 00:06:38,080
Just take some sedatives.
直接吃点镇静剂吧。

151
00:06:38,080 --> 00:06:39,080
Okay.
好的。

152
00:06:39,080 --> 00:06:45,320
So sedatives are a kind of medicine that help a person relax or that help make a person
所以镇静剂是一种帮助人放松或让人

153
00:06:45,320 --> 00:06:46,320
tired.
疲劳的药物。

154
00:06:46,320 --> 00:06:47,320
Right.
对。

155
00:06:47,320 --> 00:06:49,920
So I think it comes from the verb to sedate.
我觉得它来自动词“镇静”。

156
00:06:49,920 --> 00:06:50,920
Yes.
是的。

157
00:06:50,920 --> 00:06:55,880
And basically that is to calm down, to tranquilize.
基本上就是让人平静下来，镇定下来。

158
00:06:55,880 --> 00:06:56,880
That's right.
没错。

159
00:06:56,880 --> 00:07:00,640
So in this case, we're talking about a person, but you can also give an animal sedatives.
所以这里我们说的是人，但你也可以给动物用镇静剂。

160
00:07:00,640 --> 00:07:05,560
For example, if you want to take your dog on an airplane, the dog needs to relax.
比如，如果你想带狗上飞机，狗需要放松。

161
00:07:05,560 --> 00:07:07,000
You give it some sedatives.
你给它一些镇静剂。

162
00:07:07,000 --> 00:07:08,000
Exactly.
没错。

163
00:07:08,000 --> 00:07:13,960
And I think when he mentioned a specific name of a sedative, it's melatonin.
我想他提到一种具体的镇静剂名称时，说的是褪黑素。

164
00:07:13,960 --> 00:07:14,960
That's right.
对。

165
00:07:14,960 --> 00:07:20,320
So melatonin, melatonin is a chemical that our bodies naturally produce that help calm
所以褪黑素，褪黑素是我们身体自然产生的一种化学物质，能帮助我们平静

166
00:07:20,320 --> 00:07:21,320
us down.
下来。

167
00:07:21,320 --> 00:07:28,240
And so a lot of pharmaceutical companies or drug companies sell melatonin in a pill form.
很多制药公司或药品公司以药片形式出售褪黑素。

168
00:07:28,240 --> 00:07:31,240
It's basically, it's a chemical that helps you relax.
它基本上是一种帮助你放松的化学物质。

